"Robert C., Chamley H.","Development of early Eocene warm climates, as inferred from clay mineral variations in oceanic sediments",1991,"Global and Planetary Change","3","4",,"315","331",,,10.1016/0921-8181(91)90114-C,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-44949284371&partnerID=40&md5=f73695ec0d84d849ccb89acc99712c21","Marine Science Institute / Department of Geological Sciences, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106, United States; Géologie du Quanternaire, C.N.R.S.-Luminy, Case 907, 13288 Marseille cedex 9, France; Dynamique sédimentaire et structure. U.R.A. C.N.R.S. 719, Université de Lille I, 59655 Villeneuve d'Ascq cedex, France","Robert, C., Marine Science Institute / Department of Geological Sciences, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106, United States, Géologie du Quanternaire, C.N.R.S.-Luminy, Case 907, 13288 Marseille cedex 9, France; Chamley, H., Dynamique sédimentaire et structure. U.R.A. C.N.R.S. 719, Université de Lille I, 59655 Villeneuve d'Ascq cedex, France","Late Paleocene to middle Eocene clay mineral associations have been considered at fifteen locations from the Atlantic Ocean and the adjacent sector of the Southern Ocean, and compared to the results of previous investigations. Globally warm climates and altenating wet and arid seasons are deduced from the widespread abundance of pedogenic smectite at every location. Near the Paleocene-Eocene boundary, enhanced humidity at high latitudes and in continental hinterlands is indicated by more abundant kaolinite, while in coastal areas from low and middle latitudes increased aridity resulted in more abundant palygorskite (and/or sepiolite). Concomitant increases of kaolinite and fibrous clays are correlated with lower δ18O of benthic and planktonic foraminifers in most oceanic areas, indicating that warmer conditions were associated with enhanced evaporation at low to middle latitudes, and increased precipitation at high latitudes. This is consistent with an improvement of meridional transfers of energy, which probably contributed to the compensation of the equator to pole thermal disequilibrium increased by the global warming. During the middle Eocene, both kaolinite and palygorskite contents decreased at most southern locations, coeval with higher δ18O. Inferred cooling and reduced thermal exchanges especially characterized the southern high latitudes, and possibly resulted from plate tectonic evolution. © 1991.",,,,,,,,"Barker, Kennett, Proceedings of the Ocean Drilling Program, Part A (1988) Init. Rep. O.D.P., 113, p. 785; Barry, Chorley, (1982) Atmosphere, Weather and Climate, p. 407. , Holt, Rinehart and Winston, New York, NY; Berggren, Kent, Flynn, Van Couvering, Cenozoic Geochronology (1985) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 96, pp. 1407-1418; Birkenmajer, Onset of Tertiary continental glaciation in the Antarctic Peninsula sector (West Antarctica) (1985) Acta Geol. Pol., 35, pp. 1-30; Biscaye, Mineralogy and sedimentation of recent deep-sea clay in the Atlantic Ocean and adjacent seas and oceans (1965) Geol. Soc. Am. Bull., 76, pp. 803-832; Boersma, Premoli-Silva, Shackleton, Atlantic Eocene planktonic foraminiferal palaeogeographic indicators and stable isotopic paleoceanography (1987) Paleoceanography, 2, pp. 287-331; Boltenhagen, Salard-Cheboldaeff, Essai de reconstitution climatique Crétacé et Tertiare du Gabon et du Cameroun d'après la palynologie (1980) Mém. Mus. Natl. Hist. Natl., Sér. B, 27, pp. 203-210; Brass, Southam, Peterson, Warm saline bottom water in the ancient ocean (1982) Nature, 296, pp. 620-623; Callen, Clays of the palygorskite-sepiolite group: depositional environment, age and distribution (1984) Palygorskite-Sepiolite. Occurences, Genesis and Uses, 37, pp. 1-38. , A. Singer, E. Galan, Devel. in Sedimentol., Elsevier, Amsterdam; Chamley, North Atlantic clay sedimentation and paleoenvironment since the late Jurassic (1979) Deep Drilling Results in the Atlantic Ocean: continental margins and paleoenvironment